m><title>Nice</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/7icdK8L</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/zL5VAZd.gif" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/7icdK8L</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[CitizenK9]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>If you want something done right, you have to do it yourself.</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/fCSJH8k</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/tlkqV4f.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>They paid a contractor to come in strip the terrazzo, and put new finish down. You can see the  scratch along the edge revealing the original color.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/OXzF0PO.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>This was AFTER they "finished" it. They didn't remove all the old wax.  All those scratches and streaks are in the old wax.  The terrazzo is in great condition, considering it's 70 years old.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/t4hlvYt.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Soooo much wax.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/FItenNb.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>It looked like soggy toilet paper. It probably hadn't been completely stripped in a couple of decades.  Just scrubbed and top coated.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/xCPRwCn.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Down to bare terrazzo.</div><div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/6IbKJjB.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>5 coats of finish later and finally done.  No more scratches.</div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/fCSJH8k</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[AvsFreak]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Chemistry</title><li